## Recommendation: Use `TimeProvider` (built into .NET 8+)

Since you're targeting `net10.0`, you already have `System.TimeProvider`. It's the idiomatic replacement:

```csharp
public class OrderProcessor
{
    private readonly TimeProvider _time;
    private readonly ILogger<OrderProcessor> _logger;

    public OrderProcessor(ILogger<OrderProcessor> logger, TimeProvider time)
    {
        _logger = logger;
        _time = time;
    }

    public Order CreateOrder(string customerId, decimal amount)
    {
        var now = _time.GetUtcNow();
        var order = new Order
        {
            CreatedAt = now.UtcDateTime,
            ExpiresAt = now.AddDays(30).UtcDateTime,
            ...
        };
        ...
    }

    public bool IsExpired(Order order)
        => _time.GetUtcNow().UtcDateTime > order.ExpiresAt;
}
```

**In production DI:**
```csharp
services.AddSingleton(TimeProvider.System);
```

**In tests:**
```csharp
var fakeTime = new FakeTimeProvider(new DateTimeOffset(2026, 1, 15, 0, 0, 0, TimeSpan.Zero));
var processor = new OrderProcessor(logger, fakeTime);
// Advance time deterministically:
fakeTime.Advance(TimeSpan.FromDays(31));
Assert.True(processor.IsExpired(order));
```

`FakeTimeProvider` is in the `Microsoft.Extensions.TimeProvider.Testing` NuGet package.

